# Build context exclusions. Keeps the Docker build context small
# (the .NET 9 SDK restore step is the slowest layer; excluding these
# from the context means Docker doesn't have to send them to the
# buildkit daemon in the first place).

# Build outputs -- they live in publish/ after `dotnet publish` and
# would only confuse the COPY . . step.
**/bin/
**/obj/
**/out/
**/publish/
deploy.zip

# Version control + IDE state.
.git/
.gitignore
.gitattributes
.vs/
.vscode/
.idea/
*.user
*.suo
*.swp

# Tests -- this image is the production app, not the test runner.
# Tests are built by the separate `tests/ServantSync.Tests/ServantSync.Tests.csproj`
# and the GitHub Actions ci.yml workflow.
tests/

# GitHub Actions config -- the workflow is what builds the image, not
# what gets baked into it. Excluding this avoids drift if the
# workflow changes during a build.
.github/

# Documentation + meta files that have no runtime purpose.
*.md
LICENSE*
README*
BRANDING*
PLAN*
STATUS*
DEPLOY*

# OS / shell clutter.
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db

# This file itself + .dockerignore don't need to be in the image.
Dockerfile
.dockerignore

# The diagnostic .ps1 scripts I added in this session are
# dev-environment debugging helpers, not part of the deployed app.
# Excluded so they don't bloat the image.
scripts/diagnose-az.ps1
scripts/verify-az-fix.ps1
scripts/clear-wam-state.ps1
scripts/az-login-precheck.ps1
scripts/check-sub-type.ps1
scripts/inspect-subscription.ps1
scripts/submit-quota-request.ps1
scripts/try-regions.ps1
scripts/create-servantsync-plan.ps1

# Round-ACA-1 deploy trigger (no-op, documents RBAC grants in place):
# the Container App now has a system-assigned managed identity and an
# AcrPull role assignment on servantsyncacr, allowing it to pull the
# built image without anonymous-pull failures.
